  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Patients with hemolytic disorders (e.g. sickle cell anemia or thalassemia) are known to
      develop pulmonary hypertension. Hemolysis is where red blood cells are destroyed and their
      contents released into the circulation. It is thought that these red-cell contents cause
      constriction and thrombosis of the blood vessels in the lungs. Conversely, it is possible
      that patients with pulmonary hypertension have hemolysis.

      In this study we will be drawing blood from a range of patients and normal controls for a
      panel of blood tests related to hemolysis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
